   <title>
    <narrative xml:lang="EN">Annual Output Results</narrative>
   </title>
   <indicator ascending="0" measure="1">
    <title>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">Output Indicator</narrative>
    </title>
    <description>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">- National Media Development Strategy Document
- Media Reform Coordination mechanism (MRCG -SL)
- Codified/draft Media Bill
- Self-regulatory instruments for media (Press Freedom Charter and SLAJ Code of Practice)
- Revised media education curriculum and trained staff at the Mass Communication Department, Fourah Bay College
- Strengthened national media organizations (building blocks for media reform)</narrative>
    </description>
    <baseline year="2013">
     <comment>
      <narrative xml:lang="EN">- No National Media Development Strategy
- No Codified media law and non-existent effective self-regulatory framework for media
- Inadequate media coordination mechanism 
- Weak media organizations  
- Mass Communication Department, Fourah Bay College lack appropriate media education curriculum and adequately trained staff
-</narrative>
     </comment>
    </baseline>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2018-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2018-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1.  Eighty Percent journalists know about Sierra Leone Association of Journalists (SLAJ) New Code of Ethics 
2.  Four  SLAJ complaints committee meetings organised
3.  Guidelines on monitoring of social media developed
4.  National Spectrum allocation guideline developed
5.  Five thematic/investigative media reports (health, Human Rights, Business and Economics)
6.  Association of Communication, Journalism, Media Educators - Sierra Leone (ACJME-SL) organogram and activity plan developed
7.  Best practices on community radio stations&apos; governance and sustainability identified and popularized.
8.  Minimum wage enforced 
9. Systems and  procedures on Financial management, procurement and project monitoring and  evaluation established and four staff sessions conducted for MRCG Secretariat staff
10. Two national collaborative media (develop State of the Media Report 2018  &amp; MRCG SL Annual Programme Review) activities executed</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. There is a significant increase in the number of journalists that are informed about SLAJ New Code of Ethics. 
2. The number of media complaints brought to the IMC is decreasing as a result of periodic meetings of the SLAJ Complaints Committee.
3. All media stakeholders have agreed to design and implement an applicable and acceptable mechanism to monitor the misuse of social media. This will serve as a deterrent to abusers of social media.  
4. National spectrum allocation was proposed but was not finalized.
5. More than 10 thematic reports were produced. There is increasing capacity of journalists for thematic/investigative (health, Human Rights, Business and Economics) reporting. 
6. The Association of Communications, Journalism and Media Educators&apos; was set up and organogram designed. The launch of the Association of Communication, Journalism and Media Educators (ACJME-SL) will subsequently result to increased media scholarly work including policy research and advisory services.  
7.  Improved leadership/governance, sustainability and independence of Community Radio Stations around the country. 
8.  The sustained campaign on minimum wage to journalists (media workers) is expected to ensure payment compliance by media owners in the country.  
9. Increased competence of the Media Reform Coordinating Group (MRCG) Secretariat to effectively and efficiently coordinate media reform processes in the country (established systems and procedures on project management, financial management, procurement and project monitoring and evaluation).  
10. The 2017 State of the Media Report was produced serving as reference document on critical development in the Sierra Leone media sector. The 2018 Programme Review was conducted which reaffirmed the need to address sustainability and capacity building of media houses especially for reporting development results. .</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
